                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><b>What’s your specific research field?</b></p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;">I started my PhD focused on web security, then shifted to mobile applications. After I took my PhD qualification exam, my focus again shifted, and now I am working on health technologies, specifically IoT and mobile health devices. It’s more of a niche field. I am looking at the concerns and usability issues in emerging health IoT devices and mobile applications. </p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><b>What’s one interesting thing about that field that the rest of the team might not know?</b></p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;">I am currently looking at the Matter protocol, which is only a couple of years old. That’s a relatively short period of time, and in that time, it’s gotten a lot of attention. The protocol was designed to make IoT devices from various manufacturers interoperable. I am currently trying to understand why medical devices can (or can’t) adhere to the protocol. There isn’t a lot of work in this space. And with a lot of people using medical IoT devices for health reasons, it would be beneficial to expand Matter to include those devices. </p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><b> What’s one topic you’re interested in learning more about with SPLICE?</b></p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;">I am particularly excited to learn a bit more about the hardware side of things – hardware security.</p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><b>  If you could do another job for a day, what would it be?</b></p>
                                        <p style="margin: 0 0 10px 0;">Ah, it’s easy to forget that other jobs exist after being a PhD student for a while! I would be a shopkeeper selling potions in the 14th or 15th century. I think people were a lot less stressed back then.</p>
